Even if that option were the right one, remember that most of human population is religious to some degree, even if it's simply a vague belief in God. It's hard to see that as a mere "spin-off." (Implying it's a branch off of the main line of evolution.) True atheism is quite the minority. It seems to me that atheism would be the spin off, if we go by the fact that it's the exception rather than the rule.


 You misunderstand my usage of 'spin-off'. (Note that 'mere' was your word, not mine.) My proposal is very much on the main line of human evolution.

 The idea - not original to me, by the way - goes as follows:

 1) the evolutionary success of humankind is due to technology;
 2) early humans were at a huge advantage in developing technologies if they could formulate ideas of cause and effect;
 3) as a result human brains evolved a very powerful cause-seeking drive (ever heard a small kid responding to every answer with another 'Why?');
 4) a consequence (rather than spin-off) of this evolutionary development is a constant compulsion, as Liminus said, to make a convincing narrative of our lives and the phenomena around us. Religious beliefs arose to fill the gaps more mundane causes could not.

 Before you point it out, I realise the evidence is all circumstantial and the proposal can never be demonstrated to be true. If true, it would explain why religion in some form is, as you imply, a cultural universal: it's the product of something intrinsic to our brains, not an acquired mindset like, for example, Western philosophy. It would also explain why humans are so very bad at handling contingent or random events in their lives, always looking for cause and significance even where none exists.

